<div id="comment_65297721" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_65297721" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65297721" name="comment_link_65297721" href="//entertainment.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23662639&amp;cid=65297721" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65297721)" >It's not a production value problem</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65297721" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65297721); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~RobinH">RobinH</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~RobinH">( 124750 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65297721">		
		on Friday April 11, 2025 @11:39AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//entertainment.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23662639&amp;cid=65297721">#65297721</a>)
		<small><a href="http://slashdot.org/" title="http://slashdot.org/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65297721">I don't think it's a budget or a production value problem.  Movies are suffering because of bad writing.  The culture in the industry focuses on fourth wall breaking, post-modern ideals, and deconstructing narratives.  That's fine for an art festival, but general audiences are tired of it.  They just want straightforward storytelling that makes you feel good when you come out of the theatre.  Furthermore, audiences are tired of the gimmicks.  They don't want the same old story with a race or gender-swapped protagonist.  Those ideas were fresh and novel when the re-imagined Battlestar Galactica came out, but it's been so over-used that it's cringe.  Even if you want to throw some deep philosophical or even political ideas into your movie, you can't just vomit those ideas at the audience.  The old adage is true: you need to "show, don't tell."  That takes experience and good writing.  The reason Hollywood is in this mess is that we spent several years purging writing rooms of all the experienced writers simply because they were white, male, and old.  Then they hired a bunch of people fresh out of film school and said, "go write a movie."  You *need* mentoring.  You *need* experienced people to guide you through the early steps of your career.  This is nowhere more evident than at Disney where they put out a 100th anniversary animated feature called "Wish" that not only sported a nonsensical plot, but contained noob animation mistakes.  Nobody believed Disney could create such a poor quality animated film, yet here we are.</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_65297721">
